    <edge source="THE BIG HEADACHE&#10; &#10;&#10; BY JIM HARMON&#10; &#10;&#10; What's the principal cause of headaches? Why, having a head, of course!&#10; &#10; [Transcriber's Note: This etext was produced from Worlds of If Science Fiction, September 1962. Extensive research did not uncover any evidence that the U.S. copyright on this publication was renewed.]&#10; &#10; &#10;&#10; I&#10; &#10; &quot;Do you think we'll have to use force on Macklin to get him to cooperate in the experiment?&quot; Ferris asked eagerly.&#10; &#10; &quot;How are you going to go about forcing him, Doctor?&quot; Mitchell inquired.&#10;&quot;He outweighs you by fifty pounds and you needn't look to me for help against that repatriated fullback.&quot;&#10; &#10; Ferris fingered the collar of his starched lab smock. &quot;Guess I got carried away for a moment. But Macklin is exactly what we need for a quick, dramatic test. We've had it if he turns us down.&quot;&#10; &#10; &quot;I know,&quot; Mitchell said, exhaling deeply. &quot;Somehow the men with the money just can't seem to understand basic research. Who would have financed a study of cyclic periods of the hedge" target="1. Lack of personal motivation: Although Macklin is intrigued by the project and tempted by the possibility of being cured of his migraines, he ultimately declines because he feels that he owes too much to others and cannot take the risk of participating in the experiment.&#10;2. Fear for his well-being: Macklin is aware that his death or incapacitation during the project would not be favorable for the researchers or himself. He values his life and the obligations he has to others more than the potential benefits of the headache cure.&#10;3. Uncertainty about the results: Despite Mitchell's explanation of their discovery, Macklin remains skeptical about how a single injection could cure various types of headaches caused by different factors. This skepticism may contribute to his decision not to participate in the experiment.&#10;4. No direct financial gain: Macklin recognizes that there would be no immediate monetary benefit for him or his family if he undergoes the experiment, as the researchers do not have the resources to offer him a significant incentive.&#10;5. Potential backlash from the scientific community: As a reputable doctor and mathematician, Macklin may be concerned about how participating in an untested and potentially risky medical procedure could impact his professional reputation and standing within the scientific community.">
